The problem asks for the probability that the top four cards of a shuffled standard 52‑card deck are all from the black suits (spades and clubs).

A standard deck has 26 black cards (13 spades + 13 clubs) and 26 red cards. The probability that each of the top four cards is black can be computed without replacement:

\[
P(\text{first black}) = \frac{26}{52}
\]
\[
P(\text{second black}\mid \text{first black}) = \frac{25}{51}
\]
\[
P(\text{third black}\mid \text{first two black}) = \frac{24}{50}
\]
\[
P(\text{fourth black}\mid \text{first three black}) = \frac{23}{49}
\]

Multiplying these conditional probabilities:

\[
P = \frac{26}{52}\cdot\frac{25}{51}\cdot\frac{24}{50}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
      = \frac{26\cdot25\cdot24\cdot23}{52\cdot51\cdot50\cdot49}
\]

Simplify:

\[
\frac{26}{52} = \frac12,\qquad
\frac{25}{51},\qquad
\frac{24}{50} = \frac{12}{25},\qquad
\frac{23}{49}
\]

\[
P = \frac12\cdot\frac{25}{51}\cdot\frac{12}{25}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
    = \frac12\cdot\frac{12}{51}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
    = \frac{12}{2\cdot51}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
    = \frac{12}{102}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
    = \frac{6}{51}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
    = \frac{2}{17}\cdot\frac{23}{49}
    = \frac{46}{833}
\]

Thus the probability that the top four cards are all black is \(\displaystyle \boxed{\frac{46}{833}}\).

