The points on the unit circle are  

\[
A=(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha),\qquad B=(\cos\beta,\sin\beta)
\]

and the given vertical coordinates give  

\[
\sin\alpha=\frac{\sqrt5}{5},\qquad 
\sin\beta=\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}.
\]

Since both angles are acute, their cosines are positive:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\cos\alpha&=\sqrt{1-\sin^2\alpha}
           =\sqrt{1-\frac15}
           =\sqrt{\frac45}
           =\frac{2\sqrt5}{5},\\[4pt]
\cos\beta &=\sqrt{1-\sin^2\beta}
           =\sqrt{1-\frac{9}{10}}
           =\sqrt{\frac1{10}}
           =\frac{\sqrt{10}}{10}.
\end{aligned}
\]

---

### 1.  Finding \(\alpha-\beta\)

\[
\begin{aligned}
\cos(\alpha-\beta)&=\cos\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta\\
&=\frac{2\sqrt5}{5}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{10}}{10}
   +\frac{\sqrt5}{5}\cdot\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}
 =\frac{\sqrt2}{5}+\frac{3\sqrt2}{10}
 =\frac{\sqrt2}{2},\\[6pt]
\sin(\alpha-\beta)&=\sin\alpha\cos\beta-\cos\alpha\sin\beta\\
&=\frac{\sqrt5}{5}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{10}}{10}
   -\frac{2\sqrt5}{5}\cdot\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}
 =\frac{\sqrt2}{10}-\frac{3\sqrt2}{5}
 =-\frac{\sqrt2}{2}.
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus  

\[
\cos(\alpha-\beta)=\frac{\sqrt2}{2},\qquad 
\sin(\alpha-\beta)=-\frac{\sqrt2}{2},
\]

which corresponds to the angle \(-\dfrac{\pi}{4}\) (or \(315^\circ\)).  
Since \(\beta>\alpha\) (both acute and \(\sin\beta>\sin\alpha\)),  

\[
\boxed{\alpha-\beta=-\frac{\pi}{4}}.
\]

---

### 2.  Finding \(\cos(2\alpha-\beta)\)

First compute \(\cos 2\alpha\) and \(\sin 2\alpha\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
\cos 2\alpha &= \cos^2\alpha-\sin^2\alpha
              =\frac{4\cdot5}{25}-\frac{5}{25}
              =\frac{15}{25}
              =\frac35,\\[4pt]
\sin 2\alpha &= 2\sin\alpha\cos\alpha
              =2\cdot\frac{\sqrt5}{5}\cdot\frac{2\sqrt5}{5}
              =\frac{20}{25}
              =\frac45.
\end{aligned}
\]

Now  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\cos(2\alpha-\beta) 
&= \cos 2\alpha\cos\beta + \sin 2\alpha\sin\beta\\[4pt]
&= \frac35\cdot\frac{\sqrt{10}}{10}
   +\frac45\cdot\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}\\[4pt]
&= \frac{3\sqrt{10}}{50} + \frac{12\sqrt{10}}{50}
   = \frac{15\sqrt{10}}{50}
   = \frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}.
\end{aligned}
\]

Hence  

\[
\boxed{\cos(2\alpha-\beta)=\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}}.
\]

---

**Answers**

1. \(\displaystyle \alpha-\beta=-\frac{\pi}{4}\) (so \(|\alpha-\beta|=\frac{\pi}{4}\)).  
2. \(\displaystyle \cos(2\alpha-\beta)=\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}\).

